how do you get diphtheria i was reading william carlos williams' short story the use of force and i was wondering how the little girl in the story got diphtheria i know its caused by an acute infectious disease caused by corynebacterium diphtheriae and its highly contagious but thats not the answer im looking for so basically do you get it from being close to someone who has it or like from sharing drinks etc etc yes you are partially right diphtheria is transmitted from person to person via respiratory tract and secretions nasal discharges rarely transmission also occurs from the contact with the skin lesions and articles that are soiled with discharges from lesion transmission may occur as long as the virulent bacteria present in the discharges and lesions without the treatment with an appropriate antibiotics the bacilli persist for weeks or less and seldom more than weeks chronic carriers may shed the bacilli from their lesions even for months hope this helps regards Group A streptococcal infection Tuberculosis Anthrax Bubonic plague Diphtheria Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Common cold Psoriasis AIDS Pneumonia Syphilis Infectious disease Endocarditis Influenza Herpes simplex virus Leprosy Lyme disease Pharyngitis Conjunctivitis Diarrhea Transmission (medicine) Acne Helicobacter pylori Cholera Leptospirosis Cytomegalovirus Sexually-transmitted infection Pertussis Virus Gonorrhoea Medicine Legionellosis Medical analysis of circumcision Smallpox Escherichia coli O157:H7 Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Zoonosis Ehrlichiosis Infectious mononucleosis Erysipelas Glanders Hepatitis C Lymphogranuloma venereum Foot-and-mouth disease Foodborne illness Dracunculiasis Allergy Multiple sclerosis Human papillomavirus Chagas disease Ebola Toxoplasmosis HIV Cephalic disorder Robert Koch AIDS reappraisal Kaposi's sarcoma Hepatitis H5N1 Upper respiratory tract infection Abscess Malaria Rocky Mountain spotted fever Common misconceptions about HIV and AIDS Chronic fatigue syndrome Bacteri